DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
This domain explores integration-based accounts of the extended mind that
emphasize complementarity, transformation, and scaffolding rather than
simple parity between internal and external resources. The central insight
is that cognitive extension works not through functional equivalence but
through productive differences that transform cognitive processes. Menary's
cognitive integration framework rejects the parity principle in favor of
viewing external resources as creating hybrid cognitive systems through
integration. Sterelny's scaffolded mind approach distinguishes between
resources that merely support cognition versus those that constitutively
extend it through developmental and evolutionary scaffolding. The
complementarity principle, first articulated in physics but now applied to
cognition, captures how internal and external resources make distinct but
mutually necessary contributions to extended cognitive systems.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
Integration approaches provide philosophical frameworks for understanding
how cognitive offloading transforms rather than replicates internal
processes. They explain why external resources enhance cognition precisely
because they operate differently from biological memory and reasoning, thus
enabling cognitive transformations impossible with internal resources alone.
This directly addresses questions about what makes offloading genuinely
cognitive versus merely instrumental.

NOTABLE_GAPS:
While integration theories excel at philosophical analysis, empirical work
connecting integration principles to measurable cognitive outcomes remains
limited. The relationship between scaffolding and enculturation needs
further development, particularly regarding how cultural practices shape
cognitive integration. Recent AI integration work (2024-2025) shows
emerging interest but lacks deep engagement with earlier integration
