  number = {4},
  pages = {465--481},
  doi = {10.1007/s11097-010-9174-y},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Sterelny distinguishes between extended and scaffolded
  minds, arguing that while environmental resources are crucial to human
  cognition, they typically scaffold rather than constitute cognitive
  processes. Scaffolding involves resources that support cognitive
  development and performance without becoming parts of the cognitive system
  itself. This occurs through evolutionary and developmental processes that
  structure learning environments, enabling skill acquisition without
  requiring cognitive extension. The distinction turns on whether resources
  are reliably available during cognitive processing versus being
  developmental aids.

  RELEVANCE: This paper presents a major alternative to extended mind
  theory, directly relevant to understanding whether cognitive offloading
  extends or merely supports cognition. The scaffolding framework offers a
  way to acknowledge the importance of external resources while maintaining
  internalist boundaries. The developmental and evolutionary dimensions
  provide timescale-sensitive analyses missing from parity-based approaches.

  POSITION: Defends scaffolded mind as an alternative to extension,
  emphasizing developmental and evolutionary support over constitution.
  },
  keywords = {scaffolding, extended-mind-critique, development, High, INCOMPLETE, no-abstract}
}

